This Cheat Engine Tutorial walkthrough will teach you how to complete the built in tutorial minigame, which is built into the Cheat Engine program itself. You will learn key and fundamental concepts in how to use Cheat Engine. This video series uses Cheat Engine 6.7 but it should be very similar on the newest version. Make sure you use the regular version, not the x64 version of the tutorial so it matches the video which uses the regular x86 tutorial version.

Considerations​

If you have completed the CS420 Game Hacking Course, or have experience with Cheat Engine, you should skip the first video and if you're confident, skip this entire chapter. The first 8 steps of the Cheat Engine tutorial are incredibly basic.

Cheat Engine Tutorial Walkthrough​

The built in Cheat Engine Tutorial is made of 2 main parts:
  • 9 Steps to learn the basics of CE
  • A sample game that provides real world experience
This Cheat Engine Walkthrough is broken into 3 videos, each one covering a number of steps in the CE tutorial.

Video One​

The first video explains Steps 1-5 which are extremely beginner oriented, so skip this video if you're decent with Cheat Engine.

Things we'll learn:
  • Scan values (specifying scan type and value type)
  • Find an unknown initial value
  • Edit an assembly instruction

Video Two​

This video covers Step 6 through 9. I wouldn't skip this video, as I provide some special techniques and knowledge that you will not find in other tutorials.
  • Step 6: Pointers
  • Step 7: Code Injection
  • Step 8: Multi-level pointers
  • Step 9: Shared Op Code
Things we'll learn:
  • Understand and use of pointers with/without offsets (a pointer is a variable that contains the memory address of another variable)
  • Examples of pointers in C++
  • Freeze values
  • Code Injection/Cave
  • Multilevel pointers (to find a static address)
  • Dissect data structures with multiple addresses
  • Find the base address of an entity

Keep in mind, there are unlimited ways to solve a problem using assembly. In step 7 & 9 we found something that made sense and worked, so we used it, although I admit it wasn't ideal.


Multi Level Pointer Template​

Here's the little template I use for finding multi level pointers, it works really well if you follow the video. If you make a mistake, you can use this as a log so you don't have to start all over. Cheat Engine doesn't track this for you.
C++: 
Address = Value = ?

base ptr -> address + offset4 = address

base ptr -> address + offset3 = address

base ptr -> address + offset2 = address

static base addr -> address + offset1 = address

​

Video Three​

After completing the two previous videos we are now ready to put our concepts into practice. Cheat Engine has prepared an integrated mini game which is made to be hacked for learning purposes. You don't need external tools to complete it. Credits to @NewWinter for making this tutorial.


Having trouble?​

Having an understanding of pointers and code injection is the bread and butter of game hacking. If you find this confusing, don't be surprised. Everyone is extremely confused at this point in their studies. Keep trying, maybe re-watch the video a couple times. If you're still stuck, feel free to skip it and go through the next 2-3 videos, often times the next video will solve your frustration. But if you get 2-3 videos ahead and are still lost, come back to this one!

Video One Complete Walkthrough​

Hey scrubs, it's your boy Rake! We're gonna dive into Cheat Engine 6.7 tutorial, focusing on steps 0 through 5 for super beginners. So, buckle up and let's get started!

Step 1: Exact Value Scanning​

First, click on the "Help" button and choose "Cheat Engine Tutorial." We're using the x86 version to keep things simple. To start off, we need to attach to the process, as the Cheat Engine tutorial is a separate process. Click the process picker and select the tutorial to open it. Now click "Next" to finish the first step.

Our next task is to perform exact value scanning. We have a health variable down here, set at 100. Assuming health is an integer (a 4-byte value), we can start a scan for it. Hit "Me" and then filter the scan, so only addresses with changed values to 96 are displayed. To pass this step, we need to set the value to 1000.

Step 2: Unknown Initial Value​

Now, let's say your health is like a health bar, and you don't know your max health or your current health. To find this, we'll do an unknown initial value scan. After scanning, we have about half a million results. Hit "Me" again, and we know the value has decreased. Next, we have around a thousand results. If you hit "Me" one more time, you'll see the value has decreased by 10. We can tell the precise value to speed up the scan. Once we find the correct address, change the value to 5,000 to proceed to the next step.

Step 3: Floating Points​

In this step, we'll work with floating points. Change the value type to "float" and start scanning. Hit "Me" again and look for the address with a red change value of 96. To pass this step, change the value to 5,000.

For a "double" value type, it's basically a floating decimal point value with double the precision (8 bytes instead of 4 bytes). In this case, do a new scan for "double" and search for the precise value. We can easily find the right one, as doubles are pretty specific variable types. Change the value to 5,000 to proceed.

Step 4: Code Finder​

In this step, we'll find an instruction that accesses our health address and decreases it. Then, we'll "knop" it, so the instruction doesn't execute. Assuming the health value is an integer, scan for it and look for the changed value. Right-click and choose "Find out what writes to this address." This will attach a debugger to the process and put a breakpoint on the address. Any time an instruction writes to it, the breakpoint will be caught, and we can see which instructions touched it.

Step 5: NOP Instruction​

Now we want to replace the instruction with a "NOP" (no operation) instruction, so it doesn't change the health value. Right-click on the instruction, click "Replace with code that does nothing," and give it a name. This will save the code in the advanced options, so you can always go back to it without needing a notepad.

With the instruction replaced, the health value won't change, no matter how many times you click "Me."

Conclusion​

That's it for steps 1 through 5! In the next video, we'll tackle steps 6 through 8. Stay tuned, and happy hacking!

    Video Two Complete Walkthrough​


    Step 6: Pointers​

    In this step, we'll be working with pointers to maintain a consistent reference to our health address even when its actual memory address changes. Pointers store the address of another variable, allowing us to always access the correct address of our health value.

    Finding the Pointer​

    1. Begin by scanning for a 4-byte integer health variable. After changing its value, locate the health variable in the address list.
    2. Right-click the health variable and select "Find out what writes this address." Attach the debugger and change the health value again.
    3. Look for an address without an offset, which indicates a one-level pointer. In this case, the pointer directly points to the health address.
    4. Take the address of the health variable and start a new scan, searching for a hex value that matches the health address. The green result represents a static pointer.
    5. Add the pointer manually to the address list with an offset of zero. The pointer should now point to the health value.

    Changing the Pointer​

    As you click "Change Pointer," you'll notice the original health address becomes invalid. However, our pointer still points to the correct value, allowing us to freeze or modify the health value even as its memory address changes.

    Step 7: Code Injection​

    In this step, we'll use code injection to modify the code responsible for decreasing our health value.

    Finding the Instruction​

    1. Find the health address as before by scanning and changing its value.
    2. Right-click the health variable and select "Find out what writes to this address." Change the health value once more to reveal the instruction that subtracts 1 from the health value.
    3. Click "Show Disassembler" to view the instruction in more detail.

    Creating an Auto Assembler Script​

    1. Press Ctrl + A to open the Auto Assembler window.
    2. Select the "Code Injection" template and click "OK."
    3. In the generated script, locate the "Original Code" section. Copy the subtraction instruction to the "New Mem" section.
    4. Modify the copied instruction to add 2 instead of subtracting 1.
    5. Execute the script by clicking "Execute."

    Testing the Code Injection​

    Now, when you click "Hit Me," the health value should increase by 2 instead of decreasing. If the health value is still decreasing, ensure you've commented out the original subtraction instruction in the Auto Assembler script.

    Finding the Value and Address​

    First, we need to find our value, which is 1972. Then, change it again to 1795. Once we have the value address, Cheat Engine tells us it's a level 4 pointer. To understand multi-level pointers better, let's break down the process step by step.

    Tracing Multi-Level Pointers​

    Visual Representation​

    Imagine a multi-level pointer like this:
    Code: 
    Address = Value = ?

base ptr -> address + offset4 = address

base ptr -> address + offset3 = address

base ptr -> address + offset2 = address

static base addr -> address + offset1 = address

    We'll use the same structure in a notepad to make the process more understandable.

    Tracing Backwards​

    1. Finding the address: Search for the value (e.g., 1385), and find its address. Copy and paste it into the notepad.
    2. Finding offset 4: Determine what accesses the address, and find the offset (e.g., ESI + 18). Write the offset in the notepad (e.g., 0x18).
    3. Finding the base pointer: Perform a new hexadecimal scan for the address, and find the base pointer. Copy and paste the base pointer into the notepad.
    4. Repeat steps 2-3 for the remaining offsets and base pointers.
    5. Finding the static base address: Perform a new scan for the final address, and obtain a green static address. Copy and paste it into the notepad.

    Adding the Multi-Level Pointer to Cheat Engine​

    1. In Cheat Engine, click "Add Address Manually."
    2. Paste the static base address.
    3. Add the offsets.
    4. Name the pointer (e.g., "pointer_health").
    5. Test the pointer by setting a new value and freezing it.

    Code Injection and Dissect Data Structures​

    Creating a Code Injection​

    The goal is to create a code injection that compares the team and only provides unlimited health to players 1 and 2.

    1. Search for the health values of players and enemies.
    2. Open Memory View, go to Tools, and click "Dissect Data Structures."
    3. Find the base address of the structure and define the structure with appropriate data types.
    4. Identify the team number offset (e.g., 0x10).

    Modifying the Game​

    1. Right-click player one's health and find out what writes to the address.
    2. Show the disassembler and open the auto-assembler.
    3. Use the code injection template and modify the code to compare the team offset and skip the health reduction if the team matches.

    Testing the Code Injection​

    1. Execute the code injection.
    2. Test the game by attacking the enemy and observing the health reduction.
    3. Restart the game and verify that the code injection still works.
    Congratulations! You've successfully completed the multi-level pointer walkthrough and code injection tutorial.

    I also had same problems with integrity check bypass method shown in the video (CE 7.0). Game freezes or not switching to next level or just crashing. So I found another way to do it:
    I assumed that when everything is fine - some value is 1, and when integrity change detected - that value changes. I searched and eventually found 4 addresses of such values. Checked what writes to those addresses and one of them was constantly being changed by this command:
    Code: 
    sete byte ptr [rbx+70]
    Disabling that line of code (with AOB template script) perfectly worked for me to bypass integrity checks without problems mentioned above.
